<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
(1) Bob Kills Jim, who is a homosexual. The voting constituency of this district strongly believes that homisexuality is an evil lifestyle. The District Attorney has an election coming up. The DA decides to not prosecute becuase he doesn't want to make this case an issue in his election. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Is it likely that such a scenario is possible in today's world?  Let's remove the &quot;hate&quot; aspect and see if it changes the example.  Bob kills Jim.  For whatever reason, the DA doesn't prosecute Jim's murder.  Assuming that there is sufficient evidence to indict Bob and bring him to trial, this is a clear-cut case of prosecutorial misconduct.  But the DA's community, for whatever reason, won't get mad that the DA doesn't prosecute.<br>
<br>
Is it likely that *everyone* will abide by this DA's decision not to prosecute?  What about Jim's family and friends?  So, Jim's relatives put together a case against the prosecutor and bring it to the next highest level of legal authority.  The DA's boss recognizes this misconduct, disbars and charges the DA with misconduct, and appoints a new prosecutor.  This might take a year or two, but the statute of limitations surely won't expire before it does.<br>
<br>
In my example, it never need be the case that Jim was homosexual or black or anything else for the legal system to step in and correct the apparent injustice.  One man's murder was not prosecuted in a case where it should have been and appropriate action was taken, *within existing legal means*, to rectify it.  No new laws needed to make things right.<br>
<br>
Another thing to consider is that no one is disagreeing that a murder took place.  A crime has been committed and we currently have the means to prosecute such a crime without introducing new hate crime laws to ensure that crimes are prosecuted.  We should use the laws we have rather than simply make new ones when it strikes our fancy.  I firmly believe that the reason that hate crime laws and other &quot;frivolous laws&quot; are passed is that politicians need to be seen as actually doing something.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
And:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
The homosexual's killer has not been prosecuted, but the heterosexual's killer has. This selective prosecution based upon an individual's status classification (i.e., race, religion, national origin or sexual orientation) is unequal treatment. The Hate Crime law seeks to rectify this potential for inequality. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not a legal expert, but I'm certain that there are laws that forbid discrimination based on the criteria listed in the second quote.  I don't think it would take a Herculean leap of legal logic (Phear my alliteration skillz!) to apply those same anti-discrimination laws in situations where prosecutors are unwilling to enforce laws against a particular classification.<br>
<br>
Hate crime laws are not designed to do what you say, Torcer.  If hate crime laws worked the way that you want them to, they would simply ensure that an overlooked crime is prosecuted.  I believe that hate crime laws also add extra punishment to a crime, which is what Faithkills and I are so tweaked about.<br>
<br>
Using your previous Bob/Jim example, you seem to advocate laws that would ensure that DAs have to prosecute the homosexual murder even if they don't want to.  That's fine, I agree that they should.  I also believe that existing anti-discrimination laws can do what you want.  So, for example, Bob is prosecuted and convicted of murder.  If it were a case of heterosexual murder, Bob would get (for sake of argument) 30 years in jail.  The way that current hate crime laws work, as I understand them, Bob would get 50 years in jail if he were also convicted of &quot;hating&quot; Jim and homosexuals.<br>
<br>
What this says is that killing a homosexual is somehow worse than killing a heterosexual.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
What's worse is that hate crime legislation is often worded very broadly.  What if I were to kill a woman?  In terms of demographics, we're identical.  Same race, social background, sexuality, religion, all of it.  If it came to light that I was a misogynist and that I hated women, should I be given extra punishment because of it?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Brahma Atman Erudite Wizard Bertoxx</p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#ffffff>- </font><a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation>Graffë's Wizard Discussion</a><font color=#ffffff> - </font><a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4>Rant Forum</a> <font color=#ffffff> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.9.4.7<br>Copyright ©1999-2002 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

